About the Santa Claus Algorithm

The Santa Claus Problem

The Santa Claus Problem is a fair allocation problem where we need to distribute presents among kids in a way that maximizes the minimum happiness of any kid.

Restricted Assignment Case: In this implementation, we focus on the restricted assignment case, where each present has a fixed value for all kids who can receive it, and 0 for kids who cannot receive it.

This means that if a present has a value of 5, it will have that same value for all kids who can receive it. Some kids might not be able to receive certain presents (indicated by a value of 0).

Key Characteristics:

  • Each present has a fixed intrinsic value
  • Kids can only receive presents with non-zero values for them
  • The goal is to maximize the minimum happiness of any kid
  • Each kid's happiness is the sum of the values of their allocated presents

The implementation follows the O(log log m / log log log m) approximation algorithm for the restricted assignment case of the Santa Claus Problem, as described in the paper by Bansal and Sviridenko.
